Midgaard archives hold the most complete external record of the Scorched Wastes' pre-catastrophe administrative structure.
Keeper-era intake-gate documentation and Ledger Kingdom revenue-court records were partially preserved through salvage expeditions before undead administrative persistence made the interior inaccessible.
These records are cited in legal proceedings involving caravan charter lineages that trace back through the Keeper period — the Wastes' intake gates were the original charter validation point for much eastern desert traffic.
Current Midgaard concern: the Wastes represent a structural disruption to the eastern desert route network forcing all caravan traffic to route around rather than through the former corridor, adding transit time and cost.
Jackal Synod activity in the Wastes extends cult control over approach routes; Midgaard tracks Synod territorial claims as part of broader Synod threat assessment.
The undead administrative persistence — revenants still issuing Keeper-period ration decrees — is a documented hazard included in standard eastern desert expedition charter risk disclosures.

