Kowloon's relationship to the Scorched Wastes is archival and cautionary.
The Wastes' collapse narrative — a sophisticated administrative system destroyed when its component institutions tried to operate simultaneously with irreconcilable objectives — is cited in Kowloon's covenant law training as the definitive failure case for multi-doctrine governance.
The Twin Sovereign period, when Sand and Moon offices rewrote each other's inscriptions and converted cistern controls into dual-function ritual devices, is the operational definition of institutional incompatibility that Kowloon's joint-governance protocols are designed to prevent.
The Neon Covenant's requirement that "one ledger, one ration code" governs any shared resource is a direct response to the Wastes' ration-ledger system operating under simultaneously active contradictory commands.
Kowloon has no direct presence in or near the Wastes.

