Kiess receives Scorched Wastes intelligence as part of eastern desert route assessments forwarded through Midgaard's road warden system.
The Wastes are relevant to Kiess primarily as a factor in the reliability and cost of the eastern desert trade chain: routes that once moved through the Meridian Intake March now route around the Wastes, passing through Synod and Reaver toll zones.
The Synod's administrative vocabulary — obsession with authorized thirst, quota forms, and ration seals, inherited from the Keeper intake-gate tradition — is tracked by Kiess Trade Syndics as characteristic cult behavioral indicators.
Caravans reaching Kiess carrying goods that transited around the Wastes bear documentation gaps where former Intake March certification would have appeared; Kiess convoy compacts accept this as valid under force-majeure clauses covering "Wastes-adjacent routing."

